<LEADPARA>  COMPANION planting is a friendly, old-time garden practice. It means growing
two or more kinds of plants close together with the hope that mutual benefits
will result.;    Companion planting is not the same as successive planting --
garden arrangements where an early-maturing crop is followed by a
late-maturing crop as soon as it has been harvested.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COMPANION PLANTING GETS IT TOGETHER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Technique  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In short, companion planting uses several plantings in the garden at the
same time -- for example, radishes, spring onions or leaf lettuce can be
planted so rows of sweet corn, peppers or tomatoes can be sown between them.
The early crops mature before the taller crops shade them too much.;    One
plant may form support for another, for example, climbing green beans and tall
varieties of sweet corn planted close together. Tall plants also may become
windbreaks for tender, smaller plants growing nearby.;    Roots of some green
plants develop a symbiotic relationship with beneficial fungi in the soil
called micorrhiza. They may produce growth substances, or help the uptake of
nutrients such as phosphorous. Crops growing close together may share the same
micorrhiza, which improves growth and, it is thought, seems to indicate that
the plants "like" each other.;    There is some controversy about beliefs that
plants are able to protect each other against attack by some insects.;    A
few years ago, companion trial tests were made at Pennsylvania State
University to determine if radish could be matched with other plants for
striped cucumber beetle control; marigold with beans for Mexican bean beetle
control; thyme with cabbage for cabbage worm control; onion with carrot for
leaf hopper control; and catnip with eggplant for flea beetle control.;    The
results showed that none of these plants protected its companion from attack
by any pest.;    Another concept -- that marigolds protect nearby plants from
nematodes -- found no verification in tests at the University of Georgia. One
study showed that some marigolds attracted nematodes that are then killed
within the roots. A researcher reported this would only be useful to suppress
the buildup of nematodes but would not protect existing plants.  </TEXT>
