<HL> Technology: Parasite Infections Of Raw-Fish Eaters Show Recent Rise --- Scientists Report Main Cause Is Increase in Protected Sea-Mammal Population </HL>
<AUTHOR> Amal Kumar Naj (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<IN> FOD ENV </IN>
<TEXT>
   Parasite infections of people who like to eat raw or undercooked fish are increasing, and the main cause is the rising population of seals and other protected marine mammals, scientists reported. 

   Such creatures as dolphins, sea lions and seals are normally heavily infested with two types of nematodes whose eggs the mammals expel in their feces. 
The immature worm-like larvae are then eaten by tiny shrimp-like crustacea, which in turn are eaten by squid and some fish. 
The larvae can end up in the stomach and intestines of people who eat infected fish in its raw or undercooked state. 

   A medical rarity in the U.S. until recently, human infection by the fish parasites, called Anisakidae, has increased markedly. 
Although 50 cases have been reported -- 70% of them since 1980-they may be "the tip of the iceberg," because the infection is difficult to diagnose, the scientists wrote in the latest issue of the New England Journal of Medicine. 

   The researchers included James H. McKerrow and Judy Sakanari of the University of California in San Francisco, and Thomas L. Deardorff of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. 

   They trace the rising incidence of worm infection to the legal protection of the sea mammals starting in 1972. 
Since then, their population has "increased to numbers not seen since the 19th century," they said. 
The rising infection rate also reflects the increased popularity of raw fish, such as sushi and sashimi served in Japanese restaurants, the scientists said. 

   The group found the highest incidence of worm infections, about 80% of all reported cases, on the West Coast of the U.S. and in Hawaii. 
"The infections are related to the geographic distribution of the worm-carrying hosts," said Ms. Sakanari, a specialist on marine parasites. 

   The researchers said the worms spend part of their life cycle in such fish as Pacific salmon and striped bass and Pacific rockfish or snapper. 
The worms then end up in the bellies of the mammals when the mammals eat the fish. 

   When people eat the fish undercooked or raw, the worms penetrate the human stomach or intestines, where they die. 
But before dying, they cause inflammation and pain resembling symptoms of more-common diseases. 
The researchers said the infected people can sometimes feel the worm in their throat in a "tingling" sensation and cough up the worm within 48 hours. 

   One of the more-dangerous types of the nematodes can penetrate the walls of the stomach or the intestines. 
Then "the only way to get rid of it is to go into the stomach or intestines with a fiberoptic endoscope, catch it by the tail and pull it out," said Dr. McKerrow. 

   The researchers said such symptoms of the infection as abdominal pain, fever and nausea are often confused with those of acute appendicitis, chronic bowel inflammation, gastric ulcer or gastrointestinal cancer. 
The scientists said they are developing blood tests that could detect the presence of the worms in humans. 

</TEXT>
