<HEAD>Research on Citrus Disease Yields Unexpected Benefit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists studying a disease affecting citrus
fruit inadvertently discovered two antibiotics that might be used to
treat staph infection among humans, the Agriculture Department says.
   Staph bacteria became resistant to earlier antibiotics and are
beginning to resist the current method of treatment.
   ``In lab tests, the new potent antibiotics stopped the growth of
staph bacteria,'' said Robert A. Baker, a chemist with USDA's
Agricultural Research Service.
   He and retired colleague James Tatum discovered the compounds
after fermenting the soil-borne fungus Fusarium solani in vats.
   ``We weren't really looking for the antibiotics,'' said Baker.
``We were trying to establish a relationship between the soil fungus
and a citrus disease.''
   He said the antibiotics can be easily isolated from fermentation
broths.
   About 20 percent to 40 percent of all adults intermittently carry
staph bacteria on their skin, in their nose or on their clothes,
said Dr. Mary Young of Georgetown University Medical Center's
division of infectious diseases here.
   If a carrier gets an abrasion or cut, the bacteria can attack not
only the surface skin cells, but also enter the body and cause even
more serious problems, she said.
   ``The staph organism quickly becomes resistant to antibiotics by
producing an enzyme that renders the antibiotic ineffective,'' Young
said.
   Baker said he thinks his discovery can be effective against
staph, but such testing would have to be done by pharmaceutical
companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who were hard hit by continuing severe
weather and flooding need not lose their price support benefits, the
Agriculture Department says.
   The department announced Thursday that producers who were
prevented from planting a program crop because of weather conditions
will be allowed to withdraw from their contracts with the government
without the assessment of liquidated damages.
   They also will be able to receive prevented-planting credit from
the program crop, John Stevenson, acting executive vice president of
the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
   The action follows a letter to Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter from eight senators whose states experienced serious
flooding this spring.
   ``In Missouri alone, only about 50 percent of our corn crop has
been planted and we are more than two weeks behind normal planting
cotton,'' said Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., who spearheaded the
senators' efforts.
   Other states that suffered severely from planting delays are
Tennessee, Florida, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana, Texas and
Mississippi.
   ``Giving our farmers the flexibility to plant as weather permits
without jeopardizing their future income form the government
programs will help them through yet another difficult time,'' said
Bond.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three new varieties of sweet potatoes with
built-in defenses against insects have been developed by Agriculture
Department scientists.
   Most sweet potatoes have skins that naturally provide some
resistance to insects and nematodes, but few have the level of
resistance of these new varieties, said scientists at the
Charleston, S.C., vegetable lab of USDA's Agricultural Research
Service.
   The new sweet potato varieties are called Regal, Southern Delite
and Excel.
   ``Resistance in Excel amounts to 80 percent control of soil
insects, 75 percent of the sweet potato flea beetle and 92 percent
of the white grub,'' said plant geneticist Alfred Jones. ``That's
control you just cannot achieve with the presently recommended
chemical treatments.''
   Jones said Excel, the newest of the varieties has unsually strong
resistance to seven common soil insect pests in field tests: the
southern potato wireworm, tobacco wireworm, banded cucumber beetle,
spotted cucumber beetle, elongated flea beetle, pale-striped flea
beetle and sweet potato flea beetle.
   On test plots, the new varieties produced more marketable
potatoes without insecticide than did Jewel when it was sprayed
regularly with insecticide, USDA said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

