<LEADPARA>  Q How can I keep sowbugs and other "boring-type" insects from my melons and
pumpkins? I prefer an organic solution.;   -- M.C., San Jose  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ORGANIC SOLUTIONS CAN GIVE CHASE TO SOWBUGS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mailbag  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  A Sowbugs are not usually a big problem in the garden since they prefer dead
materials. The sowbug has 14 legs and 20 protective plates that run the length
of the body, but they really don't get around very well.;   The best deterrent
is to keep the garden clean of debris and old plant materials, where sowbugs
like to take up residence.;   To keep them off the ground, place ripening
melons and pumpkins on small, elevated platforms or inverted aluminum pie
pans. Make the platform of a square of wood with 1-by-1-inch strips nailed on
the bottom. Then, place a ring of moth crystals around each melon or pumpkin
to help ward off the sowbugs and other insects. The smell is pervasive and
repels many insects. (This works with flood irrigation systems rather than
overhead sprinkling.);   Organic gardening books suggest using tobacco dust or
pyrethrum spray to hold the line if the problem is severe. An oak-leaf mulch
and wood ashes worked into the soil are two other suggestions.;   Worm-type
invaders can be controlled using Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt). New on the
market is a control for grubs and worms that reside in the soil. It is sold as
Biosafe and consists of predatory nematodes that attack the insect. Follow
directions on the label.;   Q I planted two avocado seeds and had two 8-foot
trees until the frost last winter. Now I have four-foot plants with multiple
suckers. Can I keep these trimmed to bush types? Will they ever bear fruit?
How long before fruiting? Do they require any special care?;   -- R.W., Santa
Cruz; A Almost any plant can be kept smaller by pruning. Avocado seedlings
will bear fruit in eight to 12 years; they will have a heavy crop in alternate
years. Depending on the variety planted they will bear August to January or
October to February.;   Alkaline soils are a problem for avocados. They prefer
acidic soils, with a pH of 5.5 to 6.5. Irrigate heavily every fourth watering
to flush out the salts.;   Keep the soil in the top 18 inches moist but not
soggy. Apply aluminum sulfate if leaf tips burn, a sign of excess alkalinity.
If leaves look yellowish with the veins still green it is a sign of iron
chlorosis. Treat the condition with liquid iron.;   Fertilize your trees
lightly but regularly from early spring to late summer using sulfate of
ammonia and following directions on the bag.;   Avocados bloom in clusters in
the winter and are self-pollinating. Normally they will take temperatures to
24 degrees without damage. If temperatures drop during blooming the crop may
be lost.;   Few pests and diseases bother avocados. Snails can be a nuisance.
Keep them out of the trees by applying bait or placing copper collars around
the trunks.;   Q What is the flower used to make Hawaiian leis and is it
available locally?;   -- D.P., San Jose; A The very fragrant plumeria, also
known as frangipani, is the flower primarily used in leis. It is available at
Carman's Nursery, 16201 Mozart, Los Gatos.  </TEXT>
