<LEADPARA>  TOMATOES are a good example of the advantages of hybridizing. Many diseases
that for years have plagued these South American natives when grown in North
American gardens have been curbed through cross-fertilization and careful
breeding programs.;    The result is that, with a few exceptions, today's
hybrid tomatoes are remarkably easy to grow and maintain. Such hybrid vigor
undoubtedly has been a factor in making the tomato America's most popular
garden crop.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOOD BREEDING TURNS HYBRIDS INTO EASY-TO-GROW
CROP
TOMATOES REVISITED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Update  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     There are, of course, many non-hybrids on the market. Some remain because
they have proven themselves to be inherently disease resistant, others because
the quality of plant or fruit is worth the risk of disease.;    Then there is
the large category of non-hybrids reappearing in response to the increased
interest in antique or heirloom varieties.;    Unless you are willing to risk
losing plants for the experience of growing some unusual varieties, it is wise
to stick with hybrids -- Big Boy, Big Girl, Better Boy, Celebrity,
Floramerica, Roma, Supersteak, to name a few -- or non-hybrids that have
disease resistance.;    Look for the letters;  A series of letters following
the varietal name on seed packets and in catalogs designates which diseases
the variety resists. Roma VF, for example, means that Roma is resistant to
fusarium wilt and verticillium wilt.;    Other tomato diseases that have been
reduced through breeding include tobacco mosaic (tomatoes are in the same
family as tobacco), identified by the letter T; crown wilt, A (for its
scientific name, Alternaria); nematodes, N; and gray leaf spot, ST
(Stemphyllium). Symbols vary somewhat among seed brand names, so it is wise to
check legends.;    Diseases endure;  Diseases that have not yet been foiled
through breeding include early and late blights, septoria leaf spot and
blossom-end rot. Blossom-end rot is caused by environmental conditions that
can be corrected by the gardener.;    Few tomato varieties, even the modern
ones, are resistant to some insect pests that inhabit many area gardens in the
summer.;    (check) Blossom-end rot. This annoying disease is characterized by
a soft, discolored circle on the skin of the tomato on the side that
originally held the blossom when the fruit is first formed.;    To gardeners
unfamiliar with the condition, it does not become evident until the circle has
enlarged to perhaps 25 percent of the skin surface and the color has
blackened. By the time the tomato has fully ripened, it is lost to the
disease, which penetrates through the flesh, making the entire fruit
inedible.;    One condition conducive to blossom-end rot is uneven moisture in
the soil: watering, followed by long dry periods. The root of the
blossom-end-rot problem is calcium deficiency in the plant, a predicament
brought on by erratic water intake. In order to absorb calcium, the plant
needs water too.;    About the only thing a gardener can do is try to ensure
that the soil around tomato plants stays moist at all times. Individual
watering -- at the rate of about five gallons per week per plant -- plus deep
organic mulches will help maintain that moisture.;    (check) Tomato hornworm.
This is a fearsome creature, four or five inches long at maturity and as big
around as a gardener's thumb, an exquisite lime green studded with small black
and yellow dots and brandishing a curved red hook at one end -- hence its
name. The hornworm's appetite is mighty and its effect on tomato plants
potentially catastrophic. Fortunately it is not difficult to control.;    Its
large size should make the hornworm visible, but its coloration blends
perfectly with surrounding foliage. Look for it where you see maximum leaf
damage. The pest will eat entire leaves down to their spine, generally
preferring the topmost growth of the plants.;    Hand pick and drop the
caterpillars into soapy water. Or spray with Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt), sold
under that name in powder or liquid form. Bt is a bacteria that affects only
such soft-bodied larvae as the hornworm and other caterpillars; it is safe for
all other life forms.;    If you see hornworms sporting white bumps on their
backs that look like upright Rice Krispies, leave these alone. They are being
parasitized by a wasp whose own larvae hatch from those eggs and eat their
host.  </TEXT>
