<HEAD>Essential Oils Exports Reach Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BECKY GOMEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exports of essential oils _ the kind that
smell and taste good _ rose to an all-time high last year, says the
Agriculture Department.
   Last year's exports of essential oils reached nearly $144
million _ a 17 percent increase over a year earlier and well above
1987 exports of $114 million, according to an annual report.
   Essential oils are obtained from natural raw materials by
distillation or through a mechanical pressing process. The oils are
widely used in perfumes, cosmetics and pharmaceutical products, and
to flavor food and soft drinks.
   ``As income levels in foreign countries increase, certainly the
markets there will have an increase of these export items,'' says
Rex Dull of the deparment's Horticultural and Tropical Products
Division. ``Countries are utilizing more of them in their
confectionary products, and markets for them are growing rapidly in
these countries.''
   In fact, exports of peppermint oils increased by 22 percent to
1,510 tons, with Japan replacing the United Kingdom as this
countries largest export market for these oils. U.S. exports of
orange oil were up 61 percent, nearly doubling in value to $10.2
million. Lemon exports also doubled year-earlier levels, largely
reflecting increased sales to Japan and the United Kingdom.
   While exports of most essential oils increased, U.S. imports of
the same products fell 12 percent from 1988 to $132 million. The
decline largely reflecting smaller imports of sandalwood, vetiver,
nutmeg, geranium and cassia oils, and good crop yields by U.S.
farmers.
   Peppermint yields in Midwest producing areas were well above the
drought-damaged levels in 1988 and prices have fallen accordingly.
But demand for peppermint oil continues strong, which has kept
prices from falling further, despite the large 1989 harvest and
prospects of another good outturn this year.
   Reversing a trend dating back to the 1960's, consumers now favor
natural flavorings over synthetic ingredients. Dull, in a telephone
interview Thursday, attributed this trend to the changing health
habits of consumers.
   ``In recent years, people have become more health conscious and
want to move toward consuming more natural flavored products,'' he
said. ``People are afraid of what artificial flavoring will do to
their bodies.''
   Industry studies estimate that natural flavors now comprise
three-fourths of the U.S. market and artificial flavors the
balance, whereas the reverse was true in the 1960's.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gather up the chickens, cows and corns for the
Agriculture Department's first livestock and crop census next month.
   The department's National Agricultural Statistics Service will
conduct the survey June 1-15 to assess 1990 crop and livestock
production and inventories.
   Information provided by a sample of about 130,000 farmers and
ranchers nationwide will be used in making state, regional and
national estimates.
   ``Gathering this type of information from producers is the only
way to develop reliable crop and livestock estimates for an orderly
marketing system,'' says Rich Allen, Agricultural Statistics Board
chairman.
   ``The estimates are a working tool to help farmers and ranchers
in their decisions about production, marketing and investments in
their operations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mushroom growers have new hope in fighting
their worst enemy _ flies.
   A new natural organism might be the weapon to eliminate mushroom
flies that threaten the $500 million-a-year mushroom industry,
according to two Agriculture Department scientists. They say the
organism would allow growers to avoid using insecticides to
eliminate the pests.
   Mushroom flies breed so quickly in mushroom beds that their
increasing population usually requires growers to use insecticides
to save the crops. If not, the flies lay their eggs in the compost
that growers feed to mushrooms. Then, the hatched fly larvae eat
the mushrooms.
   But the scientists say the organism Steinernematid nematodes,
added to the mushroom bedding, burrow down into the compost. There,
these microscopic, whip-like organisms devour fly larvae.
   ``Right now, we can achieve 85 percent control of the flies by
adding 600 Steinernematids per square centimeter of compost (about
4,000 per square inch),'' says William Nickle, of the department's
Agricultural Research Service.
</TEXT>
