<LEADPARA>  Metam sodium, the pesticide that wreaked havoc on the upper Sacramento River
Valley on Monday, is so lethal that fields cannot be planted for several weeks
after it's applied.;    A powerful and versatile chemical, it is used widely
on both farms and home gardens, particularly to control weeds and small worms
called nematodes.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SPILLED PESTICIDE PACKS LETHAL PUNCH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related stories pages 1A and 12A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     And it is particularly dangerous around water, which is where 20,000
gallons of metam sodium wound up after a train derailed north of Redding on
Sunday night.;    Exposed to water, metam sodium decomposes to hydrogen
sulfide -- the gas that produces a "rotten egg" smell -- and methyl
isothiocyanate, a gas that can irritate the eyes, nose, lungs and provoke
nausea and headaches.;    The pesticide is sometimes sold under the trade name
Vapam, although Amvac Corp., the Los Angeles company that manufactured the
load that derailed Sunday, does not use that name.;    Nearly 5 million pounds
of metam sodium were sold in California in 1989, and use is believed to have
increased since then as government agencies have restricted other soil
fumigants.;    "It kills things in the soil," said Veda Federighi of the
California Department of Food and Agriculture. "It doesn't discriminate
between the weed and a good plant.";    Still, little is known about the
effects of the chemical, which was licensed in the era before rigorous
government tests. A 1988 federal law requires all these chemicals to be
retested, but little work has been done on metam sodium.;    A standard
reference prepared by the pesticide industry says it is extremely toxic to
fish, evidence of which was visible along the banks of the river Monday.  </TEXT>
